  section.page-section
    .container.px-4.px-lg-5
      .row.justify-content-center
        .col-lg-8

          p.lead.mt-5
            | There is a persistent, harmful stigma in the recovery world that taking medication to treat addiction means you "aren't really sober" or that you are just "trading one drug for another." Medical science heavily disagrees. Medication-Assisted Treatment (MAT) is widely considered the gold standard for treating Opioid Use Disorder (OUD) and is highly effective for severe Alcohol Use Disorder. In Spokane, MAT accessibility is growing, saving hundreds of lives every year.

          hr.my-5

          h2.mt-4
            i.bi.bi-bandaid.text-primary.me-2
            | What is MAT?
          p
            | MAT combines behavioral therapy and counseling with FDA-approved medications. The medications normalize brain chemistry, block the euphoric effects of alcohol and opioids, relieve physiological cravings, and normalize body functions without the negative and euphoric effects of the substance used.
          p
            | Here are the three most common medications utilized in Spokane MAT clinics:

          h3.mt-4 1. Buprenorphine (Suboxone)
          p
            | Buprenorphine is a "partial opioid agonist." It binds to the opioid receptors in the brain, tricking the brain into thinking it has opioids, which drastically stops cravings and prevents withdrawal symptoms like dope sickness. Because it is a *partial* agonist, it does not produce a "high" or respiratory depression in tolerant individuals. It is prescribed in doctor's offices and taken daily as a dissolvable film or pill.

          h3.mt-4 2. Methadone
          p
            | Methadone is a "full opioid agonist," meaning it fully occupies the opioid receptors. It is highly effective for severe opioid addictions, especially for heavy heroin or fentanyl users. Unlike Suboxone, Methadone can *only* be dispensed at a highly regulated, certified Opioid Treatment Program (OTP) clinic, meaning patients usually must visit the clinic every morning in Spokane to receive their daily liquid dose.

          h3.mt-4 3. Naltrexone (Vivitrol)
          p
            | Unlike the other two, Naltrexone is an "opioid antagonist"—it completely *blocks* the opioid receptors. If you use heroin while on Naltrexone, you will feel absolutely nothing. It is also highly effective for Alcohol Use Disorder because it blocks the euphoric, rewarding buzz of alcohol. It is famously available as Vivitrol, a once-a-month injection. You must be completely detoxed from opioids before starting Naltrexone.

          h2.mt-5
            i.bi.bi-hospital.text-primary.me-2
            | Where to Access MAT in Spokane
          p
            | Fortunately, Washington State Apple Health (Medicaid) strongly supports and covers MAT for residents. Several local organizations provide these services:
          ul
            li
              strong Spokane Regional Health District (SRHD):
              |  The SRHD operates a large municipal Opioid Treatment Program offering Methadone, Suboxone, counseling, and wrap-around services.
            li
              strong CHAS Health:
              |  Many CHAS primary care clinics have integrated MAT programs, allowing you to get a Suboxone prescription from your regular doctor in a discreet, normal clinical setting.
            li
              strong Ideal Option:
              |  With several locations in the Inland Northwest, Ideal Option specializes heavily in outpatient buprenorphine (Suboxone/Sublocade) treatment for opioids, alcohol, and methamphetamines.

          hr.my-5

